Comments.Body:
Lume components are rendered in building time, they are not intended for client side. You can include client-side CSS and JS code in the components but using the `css` and `js` named exports. For example:

```ts
// CSS code
export const css = `
button {
  background-color: blue;
}
`;

// Client side JavaScript code
export const js = `
function clickButton() {
    alert("You've clicked me!");
}
`;

// Component to render on building:
export default function () {
  return <button onclick="clickButton()">Click me</button>
}
```

This can be useful for web components or simple use cases.
If you need to ship more client side javascript, you can use the [esbuild plugin](https://lume.land/plugins/esbuild/) that can compile JS(X) and TS(X).

Take a look to the [react-todo demo](https://github.com/lumeland/react-todo) for a more advanced example, it's a web application built with React, pre-rendered in building time and hydrated in client side.

For minification, we could use [deno_swc](https://github.com/nestdotland/deno_swc) which allows us to use SWC for creating an AST, and it also has built in minification in the stringification of that AST.

```ts
import { parse, print } from "https://x.nest.land/swc@0.0.6/mod.ts";

const code = await Deno.transpileOnly("const x: string = 'asdf';");

const thing = parse(code, {
    syntax: "ecmascript"
});

console.log(print(thing, {
    minify: true,

}))
```

Hmm, I guess you're using the `slugifyUrls` plugin, right? By default, this plugin slugify the url of all files, and I could confirm that `_headers` is converted to `headers`.
I have to think of a good solution for this use case, but for now, you can configure the plugin to only slugify html pages:

```js
site.use(slugifyUrls({
  extensions: [".html"]
}));
```

@naiyerasif would be awesome if you had time to look into this issue and maybe implement the solution @oscarotero suggested yesterday in the help channel:

> The only solution I can think is store the data in a sub-key
> instead of store the data in the root of the page (page.data.toc) 
> it should be stored in a predefined key, like page.data.vfile.toc)

Here is the rehypeExtractExcerpt plugin maybe you can additionally use for testing/recreation:

```typescript
import { hastUtilToString, unified, unistUtilVisit } from "../deps.ts";

export interface RehypeExtractExcerptOptions {
  /** The var name of the vFile.data export. defaults to `excerpt` */
  name?: string;

  /** The character length to truncate the excerpt. defaults to 140  */
  maxLength?: number;

  /** The ellipsis to add to the excerpt. defaults to `...` */
  ellipsis?: string;

  /** Truncate the excerpt at word boundary. defaults to `true` */
  wordBoundaries?: boolean;
}

const defaults: RehypeExtractExcerptOptions = {
  name: "excerpt",
  maxLength: 140,
  ellipsis: "...",
  wordBoundaries: true,
};

const rehypeExtractExcerpt: unified.Plugin<
  [RehypeExtractExcerptOptions?],
  hastUtilToString.Root,
  void
> = (userOptions?: RehypeExtractExcerptOptions) => {
  const options = { ...defaults, ...userOptions };

  return (tree: hastUtilToString.Root, vfile: unified.VFileWithOutput<unknown>) => {
    const excerpt: string[] = [];

    unistUtilVisit.visit(tree, "element", (node: hastUtilToString.Element) => {
      if (node.tagName !== "p") {
        return;
      }

      excerpt.push(
        truncateExcerpt(
          hastUtilToString.toString(node),
          options.maxLength!,
          options.ellipsis!,
          options.wordBoundaries!,
        ),
      );

      return unistUtilVisit.EXIT;
    });

    vfile.data[options.name!] = excerpt[0];
  };
};

function truncateExcerpt(
  str: string,
  maxLength: number,
  ellipsis: string,
  wordBoundaries: boolean,
): string {
  if (str.length > maxLength) {
    if (wordBoundaries) {
      return `${str.slice(0, str.lastIndexOf(" ", maxLength - 1))}${ellipsis}`;
    }
    return `${str.slice(0, maxLength)}${ellipsis}`;
  }
  return str;
}

export default rehypeExtractExcerpt;
```

