I have thought about this several times, but I didn't decided a proper way to do it. One idea is adding an option to disable default plugins, so you can add it later with your own config options. For example:

```js
const site = lume({ disable: ["markdown"] });

site.use(markdown(/** Your config here */));
```

But I guess most users want to configure these plugins, not disable them. So another idea is being able to pass options to the default plugins in the lume factory:

```js
const site = lume({
  plugins: {
    markdown: {
      plugins: [markdownItContainer],
    }
  }
});
```

Another idea is providing a container in which all plugins can save their dependencies in order to configure them. For example:

```js
const site = lume();

const markdownIt = site.deps.get("markdown-it");
```

This could be used by other plugins like pug, postcss, etc. But I'm not convinced because it's useful only for the default plugins, not other plugins that the user can configure on register.

And other idea is do nothing, due the user always can create an empty Site instance, without plugins. The `mod.js` module is only a convenient way to create a site with some good defaults. But [this code](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/master/mod.js) could be used in `_config.js` file directly:

```js
import Site from "https://deno.land/x/lume/site.js";
import markdown from "https://deno.land/x/lume/plugins/markdown.js";

const site = new Site(options);

site.use(markdown())

return site;
```

For now, the way to access to the markdownIt instance, is getting the property `engine` from the template engine:

```js
const mdEngine = site.engines.get(".md");
const md = mdEngine.engine;
md.use(markdownItContainer);
```

I've added [a second argument here](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/master/mod.js#L12) to configure the default plugins, so you can pass options to markdown (or any other plugin) by:

```js
const site = lume({}, {
   markdown: {
    options: { html: false },
    plugins: [plugin1, plugin2]
  }
})
```

Yes, my example was very exaggerated. Other more common example is if you don't want to have pretty urls for a specific file. For example, it's common the page to show in case of 404 errors is `404.html`, so you can create this page with `404.html.md`.

Anyway, the thing is it's easier to simply say "If the filename contains an extension, it's used as the output extension, otherwise, the html extension is used". 

If you have to add "...except for some extensions like md or pug that are formats intended to output html, so the extension in the filename will be ignored", this introduces some cognitive load in how Lume works and make its behavior less predictable.

Maybe is this a bad design choice? Perhaps, I don't know. To me, a file shouldn't have a dot in the name, because this is introduces some ambiguity. You can request the url `/foo/bar.png` expecting a png file but it opens the html page `/foo/bar.png/index.html`.

Anyway, keep in mind that this is the default way to generate url by Lume. If you want to change this behavior, it's very easy: just [create a `url` function](https://lume.land/docs/creating-pages/urls/#urls-as-functions) in the `/_data.js` file with your own implementation. For example:

```js
export function url (page) {
  return `./${page.src.slug}/`;
}
```

