To import files relative to the current file, use relative paths (starting with dot):

```css
@import "./reset.css";
@import "./navbar.css";
```

Note that Lume will load and process all css files found in the src directory, so you will have not only the `styles.css` files but also the `reset.css` and `navbar.css` files in the dest folder. That's why they are placed in the `_includes` folder. because it's ignored due it starts with `_`. You can [ignore the other files](https://lume.land/docs/configuration/ignore-files/) with this function:

```js
// Ignore all css files but "styles.css"
site.ignore((path) => path.endsWith(".css") && path !== "/styles.css");
```

Thanks, thhis has gotten me most of the way to what I am trying to achieve. I also had to modify my `_config.ts` so that the PostCSS plugin is registered as follows:

```ts
site.use(postcss({
  includes: "/"
}));
```

The imports using a relative path starting with `./` didn't seem to work without the `includes` option set to `/`.

Thanks also for the tip on ignoring imported CSS files. I've achieved this by prefixing each imported CSS file with an underscore (similar to [`partials`](https://sass-lang.com/documentation/at-rules/import/#partials) in Sass).

Thanks for such a quick, and helpful, response, and thanks for maintaining this wonderful project!

