The plugin is very simple: https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/master/plugins/bundler.js

It only configures your site to load js and ts files as assets and then register a processor to tranform the content of these files using `Deno.bundle()`. It's an experimental plugin, I'm agree that `deno bundle` is not mature enough.

You don't need this plugin for this, because, as you can see, it's very simple. Plugins are just simple intefaces to configure your site, but you don't need them to register new loaders, processors, etc. In your `_config.js` file you can do the following:

```js
import textLoader from "https://deno.land/x/lume/loaders/text.js";

// Load *.ts and *.js input files as plain text
site.loadAssets([".ts", ".js"], textLoader);

// Process .ts and .js output files with this function
site.process([".ts", ".js"], processor);

//The function to process every ts/js file:
function processor (file) {
    const sourceFile = file.src.path + file.src.ext;
    let content = file.content;

   //Transform the content with your favorite tool
   content = myBundler(sourceFile, content);

   //Save the result in the file
   file.content = content;
}
```

Note that `loadAssets` will load all `.ts` and `.js` files in your site. If you want to load only the main file (because all imported files will be included in this file by the bundler, you have save the other files in an ignored folder. This folder can starts with `_` (for example: `_includes`) or you can ignore them with `site.ignore("my-folder-name")`.

`precompile` is supported by `jsx-preact` (not by `jsx`).

The following compile options should be enough:

```jsonc
{
  // ... other options
  "compilerOptions": {
    "jsx": "precompile",
    "jsxImportSource": "npm:preact"
  }
}
```

