> `renderSync` is used only for components, not to render/generate pages.

Oh thank you, I didn't know that. I've been wondering what that `renderSync` for.

You can make it clear on the function comment that `Engine.render()` is for pages and `Engine.renderSync()` is for components. Currently the comments only say 'Render a template' and 'Render a template synchronous' (maybe a typo of 'synchronously').

This is my first project using Typescript so I'm sure there are a lot of room for improvement for types (I greatly appreciate help for this).

`Engine.render` can return different things, that's the reason of `unknown` as return type, because it's almost impossible to cover all of them:

- Most template engines works with strings (nunjucks, markdown, pug, liquid, etc).
- There are other engines that don't work with strings natively (like React or Nano JSX, that returns objects).
- It would be technically possible to have a engine to generates binary files (pdf, images, videos, sound, etc). Usually image transformation is done with processors, but it could be possible to have a engine to output binary content. Imagine a engine that reads a music sheet and generate a sound file.
- Some template engines are sync and asynchrounous, others are only synchrounous.
- And finally we have the Generator use case.

In short, the return type could be a a string, JSX object (depending on the library), Int8Array, Generator, AsyncGenerator or a Promise returning any of the previous types.

In your example, I see some issues:

- The engine converts the result to string with `renderSSR`, but this is not always needed (for example a jsx page using a jsx layout). The React engine, [define the `toString()` property](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/master/plugins/jsx.ts#L46) to the returned object to make sure it is converted to string only when it's needed, in order to improve the performance.
- This is just a small detail, but you don't need `Promise.resolve`. `render()` is not required to be async.
- I'm not sure if in your example you take into account pages that exports a jsx object and a function returning a jsx object. For example:

```jsx
// Exports a jsx object
export default <h1>Hello world</h1>;
```

```jsx
// Exports a function that generates a jsx object
export default (data) => {
 return <h1>Hello {{ data.name }}</h1>;
}
```

In React engine, if the content is a function [it's executed passing the data and helpers as arguments](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/master/plugins/jsx.ts#L40). In this way, if the function returns a generator, it's used to generate more pages automatically, and if it's a JSX element, it's rendered as string when needed (thanks to the `toString()` property).

`Engine.renderSync` is used for more concrete use cases (for now only components, that requires to be sync) but the behavior is pretty similar. In this case, it's important to not return strings, so the components could be used as regular JSX components. For example:

```jsx
export default function (data) {
    const { comp } = data;

    return <h1>To continue, <comp.Button>Sign up</comp.Button></h1>;
}
```

In this example (it's React, I guess Nano works in similar way) Lume components are used as React components. If it returned a string, it wouldn't work.


> You can make it clear on the function comment that Engine.render() is for pages and Engine.renderSync() is for components. Currently the comments only say 'Render a template' and 'Render a template synchronous' (maybe a typo of 'synchronously').

Yes good point. I had doubts about name it `renderComponent` instead of `renderSync` but finally inclined by the latest because it's more generical name and maybe it can be reused for other purposes in the future. But this could be clarified in the comments.

