I had similar issues updating NPM packages. I think it's because Deno caches the npm package internally.
You can remove the Deno cache directory (`deno info`) or run the Lume task with the `--reload` flag:

```
{
  "importMap": "./import_map.json",
  "tasks": {
    "lume": "echo \"import 'lume/cli.ts'\" | deno run --reload --unstable -A -",
    "build": "deno task lume",
    "serve": "deno task lume -s"
  }
}
```

Once you run it with `--reload`, you can remove the flag because the new package is cached.

As you said, the first solution introduce a big complexity in the process.

The second solution looks better. Maybe a more general implementation to allow to link pages related somehow, for example `page.rel.map` could be used for other use cases.

But both solutions assume the source map is in a different page, so maybe a third solution could be provide a helper function that detect the source map location (inlined or in a different page) and retrieve this value. This solution doesn't require to modify the `Page` instance. For example:

```ts
const map = getSourceMap(page, site.pages);

// a source map was found
if (map) {
  map.page; // The page with the source map (if it's an external file)
  map.content; // The source map content (could be from the inline sourcemap or the content of the `map.page`)
}
```
What do you think?

Ok, I understand. You want to output PHP files and deploy the site to a Nginx + PHP environment to run these PHP files.
Do you want to export also HTML files or your site only exports PHP files? I'm asking this because a solution could be creating a processor to change the extension of all HTML files to PHP. For example:

```js
site.process([".html"], (page) => page.data.url.replace(".html", ".php"));
```

If you want to mix HTML and PHP pages, your solution is fine but I'd like to make this optional. For example, the renderer class could have [an option](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/pull/461/files#diff-28d0672ed21334da792e634e3e993ab0951e4d5f789f6046158b9e9274c5f0e2R9) to configure the extensions which the layouts will apply to. For example:

```js
const options = {
    layoutExtensions: [".html", ".php"],
    // ... other options
}
```

By default, it should be only `.html` extension (to avoid breaking changes) but it would allow to change it.

In the early versions of Lume, the `layout` was applied to all pages, not only HTML pages. This caused many issues because non HTML pages like `.css` or `.js` were wrapped into HTML layouts. This is the reason why it's only applied to HTML pages.

The extension is also used to detect the page format to, for example, enable the DOM API (`page.document`), or some plugins that only works with HTML pages (`inline`, `resolve_urls`, `base_path`, `metas`, etc).

I don't know if you want to use these plugins, but I supose that your use case is to have HTML-like pages but with some PHP code for dynamic content. I propose this solution:

Mark the pages that you want to insert PHP code with a variable. For example:

```php
---
php: true
---

<?php show_stuff(); ?>
```

This page is going to be exported as `.html` page, so you can change the final extension with a processor:

```ts
site.process([".html"], (page) => {
  if (page.data.php) {
    page.data.url = page.outputPath.replace(".html", ".php");
  }
});
```

What do you think?

I tried to do what you suggested earlier.
```
site.process([".html"], (page) => {
   if (page.data.php) {
     page.data.url = page.outputPath.replace(".html", ".php");
   }
});
```
Certainly it was output as a PHP format file.

In this case, it works as a complete HTML layout, so I can use all the functions and don't have to break it, so I thought it was good in that respect.

However, when using this, the problem is that DocType is output before PHP
(This is the main reason why I proposed this issue.)
https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/01c269b171b893bc96a668bd8d84241b03a45efb/core/renderer.ts#L156

It was very inconvenient because PHP sometimes processes it before DocType in headers and so on.
The reason we changed the file extension was to make it easier to understand visually and to avoid automatic DocType assignment processing.

If it is possible to avoid the automatic assignment of DocType, I think that you can adopt the method using site.process.
(I posted it without translating it by mistake, so I deleted it and posted it again)

