Many thanks @tobiasschmidt89. I think the implementation is correct, I just have a couple of points:

1. Plugins loaded by default (like this one) must be configured in the site creation function, using the second argument of `lume()` function. For example:

```js
const  url = {
  names: { url: "urlify", htmlUrl: "htmlUrlify" }
};

const site = lume(
  { location: new URL("https://example.com") },
  { url }
);
```

See the [mod.ts file](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/master/mod.ts#L17). You need to include the url Options in the PluginsOptions interface and [pass the values here](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/master/mod.ts#L45).

2. After done the step 1, in the test we need to update the [getSite function](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/master/tests/utils.ts#L23) to accept default plugins configuration as the second argument.

Hi, thank you very much for this impresive work! The ability to live-reload dependencies of modules is something currently missing in Lume.

I have some comments to this approach, let me know your thoughts:

- Prettier is not used in Deno world (AFAIK), because Deno provides a much faster formatter included in CLI. So, please, remove the config file and run `deno fmt`.
- I'm concerned about the performance of this approach. `Deno.emit` bundle all dependencies in a unique file. Not only local dependencies but also remote dependencies. This means that if you use an external dependency, it will be downloaded and the same for all sub-dependencies. So you don't have much control here, it could, potentially, download hundreds of files for every page (not sure if Deno caches this). I think this loader should be optional, not replace the default module loader (at least for now). Note that this loader is only useful on `--watch` or `--server` mode, but on build the site (in a CI environment) is not necessary.
- I'm also worried about how these changes affects to other parts of Lume (the Data and Source interfaces). I'd prefer that all this stuff was managed by the loader itself (as much as it can) instead of creating properties and functions in the Lume core. At least in a first version.

This is a PoC, of how it could be implemented in a first version:

In _config.ts file:

```ts
import createLoader from "lume/loaders/modules_reload.ts";
import moduleLoader from "lume/loaders/module.ts";

// Use this loader only in dev mode:
if (site.options.dev) {
    const loader = createLoader(site);
    site.loadAssets([".js", ".ts", ".jsx", ".tsx"], loader);
} else {
    site.loadAssets([".js", ".ts", ".jsx", ".tsx"], moduleLoader);
}
```

And in the `modules_reload.ts` file:

```ts
export default function (site) {
  const dependendants: Map<string, Set<string>> = new Map();

  site.addEventListener("beforeUpdate", (ev) => {
    const { files } = ev as Set<string>;

    files.forEach((file) => {
      const fileDependants = dependants.get(file);

      if (fileDependants) {
        fileDependants.forEach((dependant) => {
          files.add(dependant);
        });
      }
    });
  });

  return function (path) {
    const result = await Deno.emit(path, { bundle: "module" });
    updateDependencies(path, result);
    return await executeModule(result);
  };
}
```

This way, all stuff related with this loader (map of dependencies, cache, etc) is scoped in the loader factory function. I know this is not a perfect solution, but it can work to test it with real projects without affect the Lume core and then we can see how to improve it and find the best way to integrate to Lume core without need to create a factory.

What do you think?

Hi Oscar,

I forgot about Deno's formatter, prettier removed.

Performance wise it may be expensive but I think, after spending last months reviewing SSG tools, that when users see they start on development mode and the tool doesn't notice when we change a file imported by a page they're going to look somewhere else. Even if they find this solution I wouldn't use different loaders for dev & prod, that's a recipe to have everything working locally just to discover there was an error in the build. IMHO this should be the default behavior even with the performance drawback. 

Also, feels a bit dirty to import modules from `lume/core` like `lume/core/loaders/module_reload.ts`. I had to import several "core" files in order to create a plugin and all time I felt like I was binding my code to lume's internals (which I probably was).

```ts
import { Data } from 'lume/core.ts';
import JsxEngine from 'lume/core/engines/jsx.ts';
// now that I know the file structure better I see this was mistaken
import Site from 'lume/core/site.ts';
import { isPlainObject } from 'lume/core/utils.ts';
```

My first approach was to isolate this in the `module.ts` loader but as you saw that would require to change the loader signature since it requires the site and a wrapper function in order to implement this. But **most importantly this will not work without affecting lume's internals because of `Source.#cache`**, if we don't invalidate it it's meaningless to add more files to `event.files`, the loader won't be invoked.

There are more improvements I want to make like using signature overload to let typescript know exactly when `Event` has `.files` property and when it doesn't, and my final goal which is to support MDX so I'd like to move on.

