Initially, Lume supports not only dates but order numbers, so you could name your files as `1_first-article.md`, `2_second-article.md`.
I decided to use underscore to distinguish between the date/order stored in the filename and numbers that can be in the slug (for example `10-rules-of-programming.md` outputs `/10-rules-of-programing/` but `10_rules-of-programming.md` outputs `/rules-of-programing/`).

Ordering is no longer supported, so I think your change make sense. It's unlikely that the slug starts with something that can be intepreted as a date.

About the regex, probably you're right. In fact, the `createDate` function used to create the `Date` object has another regular expression. Perhaps we only need one regex, that can be used to both detect is the date exists and parse it. Something like:

```js
const match = this.src.slug.match(regex);

if (match) {
  const [, year, month, day, hour, minute, second, slug] = match;

  const date = createDate(year, month, day, hour, minute, second);
  this.src.slug = slug
  this.baseData.date = date;
}
```

