Nevermind, I was able to set it in`_config.ts` to make sure only `.md` files are processed:

```ts
site.preprocess([".md"], (pages) => {
    for (const page of pages) {
        page.data.templateEngine = ["vto", "md"]
    }
});
```

In your first example:
```js
site.use(
relations({
  foreignKeys: {
    article: "article_id",
    author: "author",
  }
}));
```

The problem is `author` key and value cannot be equal, because the plugin creates a new `author` property that overrides your `author` value. The id can be anything, it's not limited to integers. Probably something like this should work:

```js
site.use(
relations({
  foreignKeys: {
    article: "article_id",
    author: "authorName",
  }
}));
```

If you don't want to use the `id` field to link the pages, you can change it to any other value, but note that this will affect to all relations (cannot be configured individually per relation). Example:

```js
site.use(
relations({
  idKey: "slug",
  foreignKeys: {
    article: "article_slug",
    author: "author_slug",
  }
}));
```

In this example, I've configured the `idKey` as "slug" so all related pages must have a `slug` key. And, for consistency, I've changed the foreign keys names to include `_slug` as suffix.

