Hi, @Brixy 

> Is it/how is it possible to use a Hugo-like folder structure for a blog?

The url generation in Lume doesn't work exactly like Hugo: The date from the path is extracted only if it's in the filename but not in the folder name. In your example, `/blog/2022-05-01_first-post/index.md` outputs to `/blog/2022-05-01_first-post/index.html`, but `blog/2022-05-02_second-post.md` outputs to `blog/second-post/` (because the date is defined in the filename, not in the folder). I think this could be implemented easily but it's not available right now.

Fortunately, you can use javascript functions to customize the final url of the pages [See this](https://lume.land/docs/creating-pages/urls/#urls-as-functions). You can create a `blog/_data.js` file and export the `url` function that will be used to generate the url of the post as you like:

```js
export function url(page) {
    const path = page.src.path; // The path name without extension (ex: /blog/2022-05-01_first-post/index)
    const url = generateMyOwnUrl(path); // This returns something like /blog/first-post/
    return url;
}
```

Another way is by creating a preprocessor, that can change the url before rendering the page:

```js
// Preprocess all html pages
site.preprocess([".html"], (page) => {
    const path = page.src.path; // The path name without extension (ex: /blog/2022-05-01_first-post/index)
    const url = generateMyOwnUrl(path); // This returns something like /blog/first-post/
    page.url = url; // Assign the new url to the page
});
```

> Is it possible to copy assets (and process images with Imagick) from within these folders?

Yes. If you are going to use imagick plugin, just import it in your config file and that's all. By default the extensions `.jpg`, `.jpeg` and `.png` are loaded but you can change it.

```js
import lume from "lume/mod.ts";
import imagick from "lume/plugins/imagick.ts";

export default lume()
    .use(imagick({
        extensions: [".jpg"], //If you only want to load jpg files
    ));
```


> Is there an equivalent of Eleventy’s paired shortcodes.

Yes, you have to define the helper as `type: "tag"` ([See this](https://lume.land/docs/configuration/filters/#helpers)). In your example:

```js
site.addHelper('blockquote', blockquote, { body: true, type: "tag" });
```

The combination of removing the `/posts` folder from path + using generating posts from folders and markdown files (`/src/posts/post-1/` and `/src/post-2.md`) + using `imagick` with all images and assets living in the posts’ folders seems a bit tricky.

So for reference, this is what I have come up with – in case anyone might need it.

There are probably more elegant solutions; but this works ;-)

```
# _config.ts

site
  .copy('static', '.')
  .copy(
    ['.docx', '.mp3', '.mp4', '.pdf'],
    (path) => path.replace('/posts', ''),
  );

site.preprocess(['.jpg', '.png', '.gif'], function (page) {
  page.data.layout = undefined;
});

site.process(['.jpg', '.png', '.gif'], function (page) {
  page.dest.path = page.dest.path.replace('/posts', '');
});


# /src/posts/_data.yml

export function url(page) {
  let path = page.dest.path.replace('/posts', '');
  if (!path.includes('/index') && page.src.ext == '.md') {
    path = path + '/index';
  }
  return path + page.src.ext.replace('.md', '.html');
}

export const imagick = [
  {
    resize: [200, 200],
    suffix: '-small',
  },
  {
    resize: [200, 200],
    suffix: '-small',
    format: 'webp',
  },
  {
    resize: [600, 600],
  },
  {
    resize: [600, 600],
    format: 'webp',
  },
];
```

