The [`templateEngine` variable](https://lume.land/docs/core/multiple-template-engines/) allows to define a engine to render the page.

```js
// docs.tmpl.js
export default function * ({ docData }) {
	for (const doc of docData) {
		yield {
			url: `docs/${doc.title}.md`,
			content: doc.content,
                        templateEngine: "njk"
		}
	}
}
```

I'm thinking of allowing to render the layout for non-html pages only if the layout is defined directly in the page data (not inherited from a _data files).

I think it's not possible to export a variable with a dot in the name. This will fail

```js
export const title.en = "Title";
export const title.gl = "Título";
```

But you can export the [language variables](https://lume.land/plugins/multilanguage/#language-root-variables):

```js
export const en = {
  title: "Title",
}

export const gl = {
  title: "Título",
}
```

That would be a nice plugin, and I think it wouldn't be hard.

The `page` variable in your templates contains the current page object.
`page.parent` returns the directory object where the page is stored.

So I imagine something like this should work:

```ts
import { Page, Directory } from "lume/core.ts";

interface Link {
  text: string;
  url: string;
}

function getBreadcrumb(page: Page) {
  const links: Link[];
  let currentDirectory = page.parent;

  while  (currentDirectory) {
    const indexPage = currentDirectory.pages.get("index.md");
    links.push({
      text: indexPage.data.title,
      url: indexPage.data.url
    });
    currentDirectory = currentDirectory.parent;
  }

  return links;
}
```

You can use this helper in your templates:

```njk
<ol>
    {% for item in getBreadcrumb(page) %}
    <li>
      <a href="{{ item.url }}">{{ item.text }}</a>
    </li>
    {% endfor %}
</ol>
```

To include the version in the url, you can use [the `url` function](https://lume.land/docs/creating-pages/urls/#urls-as-functions). For example, create `_data.js` file in the folder containing the files do you want to rewrite:

```js
// my-files/_data.js

const version = "v1.2.3";

export function url(page) {
  return `./${page.src.slug}${version}${page.src.ext}`
}
```

Yes, sure. If you only want to use the data to generate json files, you can create a pages from a js/ts file:

```js
// ./api.tmpl.js

// Fetch your data from anywhere
const response = await fetch("https://my-api.com/data.json");
const data = await response.json();

// Export it as you want. You even can generate multiple files using a generator
export default function * () {
    for (const item of data) {
        yield {
          url: `/api/${item.id}.json`,
          content: JSON.stringify(item),
        }
    }
}
```
More info here: https://lume.land/docs/core/multiple-pages/

